\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
1.
 Purpose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The purpose of this policy is to govern the detection,
 intake,
 triage,
 resolution,
 and closure of operational incidents within the Elko County Information Operations Department.
 An operational incident is any unplanned interruption to,
 or degradation of,
 an IT service caused by a non-malicious technical failure.
 The objective of this policy is speed of restoration —
 returning County staff to full operational capability as rapidly as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy establishes the mandatory workflow for responding to operational incidents,
 defines the single command authority for incident management,
 codifies the conditions under which operational incidents transfer jurisdiction to Chapter 4 cybersecurity incident protocols,
 and defines the objective triggers by which closed incidents spawn formal Problem investigations under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
2.
 Scope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy applies to all Information Operations Department personnel and governs all operational incidents involving County IT assets and services,
 regardless of the channel through which the incident was identified or reported.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Operational incidents within the scope of this policy include,
 but are not limited to:
 hardware failures and component degradations,
 application crashes and service outages,
 network connectivity failures,
 ISP disruptions,
 failed or rollback-required software patches,
 account or access failures not involving unauthorized access,
 and any other unplanned event that interrupts or degrades normal IT service delivery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy does not govern malicious events,
 suspected or confirmed unauthorized access,
 ransomware or malicious code activity,
 data spillage involving Criminal Justice Information (CJI) or Personally Identifiable Information (PII),
 insider threats,
 or any other event involving an Indicator of Compromise (IoC) as defined in Chapter 4.
 Those events are governed exclusively by Chapter 4 (Incident Response).
 Section 6.2 of this policy defines the mandatory procedure for transferring jurisdiction to Chapter 4 when an IoC is discovered during an otherwise routine operational incident.
\end_layout

